column18:
Asian Americans’ Experiences of Discrimination and Political Participation Survey 


BACKGROUND 

You are being invited to participate in a voluntary research study. Before you decide, it is important for you to understand why the research is being done and what it will involve. Please take time to read the following information carefully. Ask us if there is anything that is not clear or if you would like more information.



The purpose of the study is to explore the relationship between discrimination and political engagement of Asian Americans, and address the significant gap in the current research on the potential impact of political and societal discrimination on Asian Americans’ political behavior. Your input will help to improve better awareness and create a more inclusive environment for the community. This study is carried out by the researchers from the Department of Political Science at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign and supported by the Department of Asian American Studies.



STUDY PROCEDURE 

This survey will take you approximately 10 minutes to complete this study. Questions will be asked about discrimination and political participation. The study procedures are completing an online survey comprised of demographic information, hypothetical situations, emotional reactions and political participation.



This research is considered experimental and the group of study participants you will be assigned to will be chosen by chance, like flipping a coin. Neither you nor the study team will choose which study group you are assigned to. You will have an equal chance of being assigned to any given group.



RISKS 

The risks of this study are minimal. Risks related to this research may include psychological distress or discomfort due to the nature of the study topic.You may feel upset thinking about the discrimination targeting Asian Americans. These risks are similar to those you experience when discussing with others. If you feel upset from this experience, you can tell us, and we will tell you about resources available to help.



BENEFITS 

There are no direct benefits for taking part in this study. However, we hope the information we get from this study may help develop a greater understanding of Asian Americans’ discriminatory experiences and political behavior in the future. 

 

HOW WILL THE RESEARCHERS PROTECT MY INFORMATION? 

Only research team members will have access to your survey responses. All team members will maintain confidentiality to the extent of laws and university policies. We will not collect your names or contact information either.


No members of the research team will be monitoring your responses. No follow up will be provided outside of the debriefing document at the end of the study.



WHO WILL HAVE ACCESS TO THE INFORMATION COLLECTED DURING THIS RESEARCH STUDY? 

Your survey responses will be kept confidential and available only to authorized members of the research team. Faculty, students, and staff who may see your information will maintain confidentiality to the extent of laws and university policies. Personal identifiers will not be published or presented. Your de-identified information could be used for future research without additional informed consent.


HOW MIGHT THE INFORMATION COLLECTED IN THIS STUDY BE SHARED IN THE FUTURE? 

We will keep the information we collect about you during this research study for study record-keeping and for potential use in future research projects. De-identified data from this study may be shared with the research community, with journals in which study results are published, and with databases and data repositories used for research.



PERSON TO CONTACT 

If you have questions, complaints or concerns about this study, you can contact the Principal Investigator: Dr. Cara Wong, Associate Professor at the Department of Political Science, University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign, at carawong@illinois.edu.



If you have any questions about your rights as a research subject, including concerns, complaints, or to offer input, you may call the Office for the Protection of Research Subjects (OPRS) at 217-333-2670 or e-mail OPRS at irb@illinois.edu.



VOLUNTARY PARTICIPATION 

Your participation is voluntary and you can choose to skip any question in the survey without penalty. You also are free to withdraw your consent and discontinue participation at any time. Your decision of whether or not to participate, or to withdraw after beginning participation, will not affect your current or future dealings with the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign.



CONSENT 

Please print this consent form if you would like to retain a copy for your records.

 

By signing this consent form, I confirm I have read the information in this consent form and have had the opportunity to ask questions. I also certify that I am physically located in the United States at the time of study procedure completion. I will be given a signed copy of this consent form. I voluntarily agree to take part in this study.



Thank you for taking the time to help us with this important project!

column33:
Imagine that a friend tells you that when they were dealing with issues at the immigration office, the officer examined their travel documents for a very long time, and each questions seemed to show suspicion, which was not the case for other non-Asian looking people.

How would you feel if this situation happened to you?
column34:
Suppose that an Asian colleague told you that they were just confronted by a white  police officer who said, “Hey, you should go back to your own country, you Asian a**hole!”

How would you feel if this situation happened to you?
column35:
Imagine that a friend tells you that when they went to a restaurant, the server frequently overlooked them when taking orders or refilling drinks, often focusing more on other tables of non-Asian-looking guests. Despite your friends requesting service, the server was unresponsive and failed to act promptly.

How would you feel if this situation happened to you?
column36:
Suppose that an Asian colleague told you they were just confronted by a person in a store who said, “Hey, you should go back to your own country, you Asian a**hole!”

How would you feel if this situation happened to you?
column37:
Imagine that a friend described to you how voter turnout in the 2020 U.S. general election soared to levels not seen in decades yet still lagged behind many countries.   In the meantime, they have been required to register and turn out to vote on the Election Day.

How would you feel if this situation happened to you?
column38:
Suppose that a colleague told you that they overheard a group of individuals discussing their involvement in a potential mail-in voting fraud during a recent election.

How would you feel if this situation happened to you?
